"DOMAINS_SMART_WORKER_PROMPT","4","*","*","92","Output is comprehensive with 20 domains covering all major business areas for a health insurance payer. All domains align with provided data domains and core business processes. Division classification follows the interleaved operations/business model with 11 operations (55%), 6 business (30%), and 3 corporate (15%), meeting the 80%+ operations+business requirement. SSOT principle maintained with member as party SSOT, product as catalog SSOT, and billing as revenue SSOT. All domain names are single-word, singular, SQL-compliant, and industry-standard. No analytics/reporting domains included. Descriptions incorporate industry jargon appropriately (COB, EOB, HCC, RAF, HEDIS, etc.). Minor consideration: credentialing could arguably be merged with provider domain, but industry practice treats credentialing as a distinct operational function with separate teams, so keeping it separate is defensible. All validation rules followed."
"DOMAINS_SELECTION_JUDGE_PROMPT","1","*","*","93","Final output contains 21 domains within the 15-25 range requirement. All domains align with provided business context data domains and core processes. SSOT principles strictly maintained - no overlapping ownership of business concepts. Division classification follows interleaved model with appropriate operations/business/corporate distribution. All domain names are single-word, singular, SQL-compliant, and pass the 'department name test'. No analytics, reporting, or technical infrastructure domains included per rules. Industry-standard terminology used throughout (HCC, RAF, HEDIS, COB, etc.). Standards list comprehensive with 9 key regulatory bodies. Source attribution provided for all domains enabling traceability. The government domain addition addresses a gap in Claude models' outputs for this significant LOB. Minor deduction for potential debate on eligibility vs enrollment separation, but the distinction is defensible based on different EDI transactions (834 vs 270/271) and operational teams."
