"ATTRIBUTES_SMART_WORKER_PROMPT","25","product","plan_network","92","I have generated a comprehensive schema for the plan_network data product with 65 attributes covering all major business dimensions: identifiers (plan_network_id, plan_id, network_id), network characteristics (network_tier, network_type, geographic coverage), operational attributes (status, effective/termination dates, primary network flag), provider counts (PCP, specialist, hospital, facility), cost-sharing parameters (copay/coinsurance by tier), coverage flags (telehealth, behavioral health, pharmacy, DME, vision, dental), regulatory compliance (network adequacy status, CMS contract numbers, state filing IDs, accreditation statuses), quality metrics (star ratings, member satisfaction), and administrative attributes (approval dates, comments). The schema aligns with the operational systems mentioned (QNXT, HealthEdge HealthRules for network management) and references all relevant governing bodies (CMS, ACA, NCQA, URAC, state DOIs). All attributes follow naming conventions (snake_case, no product prefix), use appropriate data types, include proper PII/confidentiality tags where applicable, and have clear business glossary terms with full abbreviation expansions. I applied semantic duplicate prevention (e.g., using termination_date not end_date, created_date not creation_date). The attribute count of 65 is within the suggested range and represents comprehensive coverage for a plan-network mapping entity in the health insurance payer industry. Minor deduction: I could have potentially included a few additional niche attributes such as network performance metrics or specific CMS reporting fields, but the current set represents all essential and most extended business attributes a domain expert would expect."
"ATTRIBUTES_SMART_WORKER_PROMPT","26","product","enrollment_window","92","I have generated a comprehensive schema for the enrollment_window data product with 65 attributes covering all major business dimensions: identification (ID, code, name), classification (window type, LOB, product type, market segment, qualifying event type), temporal attributes (start/end dates, coverage effective date, plan year, notification date, various lifecycle timestamps), status and flags (status, is_active, is_extended, various eligibility flags), operational attributes (enrollment channels, SLA, capacity management, documentation requirements), regulatory compliance (regulatory authority, compliance validation, references), financial attributes (commission rates, premium due dates, subsidy information), and audit trail (created/modified/approved/closed timestamps and users). The schema aligns with CMS, ACA, ERISA, COBRA, and state insurance regulations. All attributes follow naming conventions (snake_case, no product prefix except for PK), use appropriate data types, include proper value enumerations where applicable, and reference relevant regulatory standards. I have included attributes that would be found in policy administration systems like Facets, QNXT, and Oracle Health Insurance. The attribute count of 65 is within the suggested range and represents comprehensive coverage of what a business user would need for enrollment window management, reporting, and compliance. I deducted points because: (1) I included some audit/technical attributes (created_by, last_modified_by, source_system) which could be considered borderline technical rather than pure business attributes, though they do serve business audit purposes; (2) the enrollment_capacity_percentage attribute is arguably a calculated metric rather than a stored business attribute, though it could be materialized for performance. These are minor judgment calls in an otherwise comprehensive and production-ready schema."
