"ATTRIBUTES_SMART_WORKER_PROMPT","57","provider","provider_termination","92","I have generated a comprehensive provider_termination schema with 68 attributes covering all major business dimensions: provider identification (provider_id, NPI, TIN, name, type, specialty), contract and network context (contract_id, network_id, network_type, LOB), termination details (reason codes, category, initiated_by, dates), regulatory compliance (member notification, continuity of care, claims runout, NPDB/state board/CMS reporting), appeals process (appeal filed, status, resolution), reinstatement eligibility, audit trail (processed_by, approved_by, timestamps), service location details, network adequacy impact, and financial settlement. All attributes follow naming conventions (no product prefix redundancy), use appropriate data types, include proper PII/confidentiality tags where applicable, and align with health insurance payer industry standards (CMS, NCQA, NPDB, state regulations). The schema reflects real-world provider termination workflows in systems like Facets, QNXT, or HealthEdge HealthRules. I have avoided technical ETL fields, calculated metrics, and semantic duplicates. The attribute count of 68 is within the suggested range and represents thorough coverage of the provider termination lifecycle. Minor deduction for potential edge cases that might exist in highly specialized termination scenarios (e.g., multi-state provider terminations with varying state requirements), but the core business attributes are comprehensively covered."
"ATTRIBUTES_SMART_WORKER_PROMPT","58","provider","provider_identifier","92","I have generated a comprehensive provider identifier schema with 63 attributes covering all major identifier types relevant to healthcare payer operations: NPI (with full lifecycle tracking), TIN (with type and status), state licenses, DEA numbers, Medicare PTAN, Medicaid IDs, CLIA numbers, taxonomy codes, and board certifications. Each identifier category includes not just the identifier itself but also associated metadata such as status, effective/expiration dates, verification information, and regulatory context. The schema aligns with the operational systems mentioned (Facets, QNXT, HealthEdge, Availity) which all manage provider identifiers for network management and claims processing. I included comprehensive verification and data quality attributes (verification_date, verification_method, verification_status) which are critical for credentialing and compliance. All attributes follow naming conventions (no product prefix, snake_case, semantic clarity), include appropriate PII/confidential tags for sensitive identifiers (TIN, DEA, license numbers), and reference relevant governing bodies (CMS, DEA, CLIA, state boards, NUCC). The schema covers the full lifecycle of identifiers from enumeration/issuance through expiration/termination. I included three timestamp/source tracking attributes at the end which are borderline technical but provide essential data lineage context that business users need for data quality assessment. The attribute count (63) is well within the suggested range and every attribute has clear business value for provider network management, credentialing, claims processing, and regulatory compliance. Minor consideration: I included record_created_timestamp, record_updated_timestamp, and data_source which could be considered technical metadata, but these are essential for data quality, audit trails, and understanding data lineage in a lakehouse environment where multiple source systems feed provider data. These are commonly expected by business users for data governance purposes."
