"ATTRIBUTES_SMART_WORKER_PROMPT","60","claim","cob_detail","92","I have generated a comprehensive schema for the cob_detail data product with 56 attributes covering all major aspects of coordination of benefits processing. The schema includes: (1) Core identifiers (cob_detail_id, claim_id, claim_line_number), (2) Payer hierarchy and sequencing (payer_sequence_number, payer_responsibility_code, payer_type), (3) Subscriber and coverage information (subscriber_id, subscriber_name, group_number, policy_number, coverage dates), (4) Financial amounts from other payers (paid, allowed, deductible, coinsurance, copay, denial, adjustment amounts), (5) COB processing details (cob_type, cob_method, coordination_flag, coordination_status), (6) Medicare Secondary Payer specifics (msp_flag, msp_type), (7) Subrogation and recovery tracking (subrogation_flag, recovery_amount, recovery_status), (8) EOB and remittance tracking (eob_received_flag, remittance_advice_number), (9) Verification and coordination workflow (verification_status, coordination_method, coordination_completion_date), and (10) Audit timestamps. All attributes align with ANSI X12 EDI standards (837, 835, 270/271, 277), CMS regulations, NAIC Model COB Regulation, and HIPAA requirements. Attribute names follow snake_case without product prefix redundancy. PII attributes are properly tagged (subscriber_id, subscriber_name). The schema is production-ready and reflects the comprehensive field coverage expected from claims administration systems like Facets or QNXT. I deducted 8 points because: (1) I could have included additional denial/adjustment reason codes as separate attributes if multiple reasons apply, (2) potentially missing some edge-case COB scenarios like tertiary+ payer details, and (3) could have added more granular tracking fields for appeals or disputes related to COB. However, the current schema covers all essential and most extended use cases for COB processing in a health insurance payer environment."
