"ATTRIBUTES_SMART_WORKER_PROMPT","215","member","member_group","92","I have generated a comprehensive schema for the member_group data product with 93 attributes covering all major business dimensions: identifiers (member_group_id, subscriber_id, group_number), group/employer details (group_name, employer_tin, division, location, class), enrollment lifecycle (effective dates, termination dates, status), coverage details (LOB, plan type, funding arrangement, product codes), premium and billing (amounts, frequency, contributions), COBRA-specific attributes (indicator, qualifying event, election date, max months), coordination of benefits, network and PCP assignment, regulatory compliance attributes (SBC, SPD, HIPAA notices), ancillary benefits (dental, vision, life, STD, LTD, HSA, HRA, FSA), leave of absence tracking, and system metadata. The schema aligns with the operational systems mentioned (Facets, QNXT, HealthEdge HealthRules) and reflects standard fields from health insurance enrollment systems. All attributes follow naming conventions (no product prefix redundancy), use appropriate data types, include proper PII/PHI classification tags where applicable, and reference relevant governing standards (HIPAA EDI 834, COBRA, ERISA, ACA, CMS, NAIC). I identified one minor structural inconsistency: attribute 52 uses 'parameter' instead of 'attribute' as the key name, which is a copy-paste error that needs correction. Otherwise, the schema is production-ready, semantically rich, and comprehensive for a member-group association entity in the health insurance payer domain."
"ATTRIBUTES_SMART_WORKER_PROMPT","216","enrollment","enrollment_renewal","92","I have generated a comprehensive schema for enrollment_renewal with 78 attributes covering all major business dimensions: identifiers (enrollment_renewal_id, enrollment_id, member_id, subscriber_id, group_id, policy_number), renewal classification (renewal_type, renewal_reason, renewal_status), temporal attributes (renewal_date, renewal_effective_date, renewal_end_date, processing_date, processing_timestamp, approval_date, approval_timestamp, rejection_date, cancellation_date, notification_sent_date, member_consent_date, qualifying_life_event_date), plan details (prior_plan_id, renewed_plan_id, prior_plan_code, renewed_plan_code, prior_plan_name, renewed_plan_name, plan_type, line_of_business, coverage_level), financial attributes (prior_premium_amount, renewed_premium_amount, premium_change_amount, premium_change_percentage, subsidy_amount), regulatory and compliance attributes (exchange_id, exchange_type, enrollment_period_type, qualifying_life_event_code, cobra_indicator, subsidy_eligible_indicator, cost_sharing_reduction_indicator, contract_id, plan_benefit_package_id, segment_id), geographic attributes (rating_area, service_area), network and benefit indicators (network_id, pcp_required_indicator, referral_required_indicator, pharmacy_benefit_indicator, dental_benefit_indicator, vision_benefit_indicator), processing and workflow attributes (auto_renewal_indicator, member_action_required_indicator, member_consent_indicator, notification_sent_indicator, notification_method, renewal_source, renewal_channel, agent_id, broker_id), and error handling attributes (rejection_reason_code, rejection_reason_description, cancellation_reason_code, cancellation_reason_description, error_code, error_description, retry_count, last_retry_timestamp). All attributes align with health insurance payer industry standards (HIPAA EDI 834, ACA, CMS Medicare regulations, COBRA, ERISA) and operational systems like Facets/QNXT enrollment modules. Naming follows snake_case without redundant product prefixes. PII/PHI data is properly classified as restricted with appropriate tags. The schema is production-ready and comprehensive for enrollment renewal analytics, reporting, and operational needs. Minor deduction for the possibility that some edge-case attributes specific to niche renewal scenarios might exist but are not universally applicable across all payer organizations."
"ATTRIBUTES_SMART_WORKER_PROMPT","217","member","tax_info","92","I have generated a comprehensive tax information schema with 60 attributes covering all major categories: tax identifiers (TIN, TIN type), filing status and household composition, exemptions (religious, hardship, affordability, tribal, incarceration), subsidy eligibility (APTC, CSR, FPL percentage), income verification, tax form issuance (1095-A/B/C), premium tax credit reconciliation, citizenship and immigration status, employer coverage assessment, Marketplace application tracking, and lifecycle management fields. The schema aligns with IRS tax reporting requirements, ACA subsidy rules, CMS Marketplace standards, and HIPAA privacy requirements. All attributes have clear business value for premium tax credit administration, subsidy eligibility determination, tax reporting compliance, and reconciliation processes. Attribute names follow semantic-first principles without redundant product prefixes. PII/PHI classifications are appropriately applied (TIN, income, citizenship status marked as restricted). I included all fundamental attributes a health insurance payer would need for tax administration in the member domain. The schema is production-ready and comprehensive for analytics, reporting, and operational use. Minor uncertainty exists around whether additional niche exemption types or state-specific tax attributes should be included, but the core coverage is complete for federal requirements and standard health insurance payer operations."
