"ATTRIBUTES_SMART_WORKER_PROMPT","238","marketing","vendor_contract","92","I have generated a comprehensive vendor contract schema with 67 attributes covering all major business dimensions: contract identification (contract_number, vendor_name, vendor_tin), classification (vendor_type, contract_type, line_of_business, campaign_type), lifecycle management (effective_date, expiration_date, contract_status, approval_date, signed_date), financial terms (contract_value_amount, payment_terms, billing_frequency, rate_type, hourly_rate_amount, daily_rate_amount, fixed_fee_amount), performance management (performance_bonus_eligible_flag, performance_rating, sla_response_time_hours), legal and compliance (termination_clause, confidentiality_agreement_flag, business_associate_agreement_flag, phi_access_flag, insurance_requirement_flag, liability_limit_amount, indemnification_clause, intellectual_property_ownership, governing_law_state, dispute_resolution_method), contact information (primary_contact_name, primary_contact_email, primary_contact_phone, contract_owner_name), and regulatory compliance (cms_marketing_approval_required_flag, regulatory_compliance_requirements). All attributes follow naming conventions (no product prefix redundancy), use appropriate data types, include proper PII/confidentiality tags, and reference relevant standards (HIPAA, CMS, contract management best practices). The schema is aligned with Healthcare's marketing domain and vendor management needs, covering contracts for digital marketing agencies, creative agencies, media buying, and other marketing vendors supporting Commercial, Medicare, and Marketplace lines of business. I applied semantic-first naming, avoided duplicates, and ensured each attribute has clear business value. The attribute count of 67 is within the suggested range and represents comprehensive coverage for a vendor contract entity in the health insurance payer industry. Minor deduction for potential edge cases that might exist in