"BATCH_SEMANTIC_FK_RESOLUTION","1","*","*","82","I am 82% confident in these resolutions. HIGH confidence resolutions (28 out of 45) include: exact PK matches (provider_id → provider.provider), domain-level resolutions with clear primary entities (member_id → member.member_profile), self-referential FKs (master_lead_id → lead.lead_id), and semantic matches with strong industry alignment (subscriber_id → member_profile, plan_id → product_plan). MEDIUM confidence resolutions (10 out of 45) include: user_id → service.agent (agents represent users but naming differs), facility_id → provider.location (semantic match but not exact), pharmacy_id → contract_pharmacy (domain-level but could be other pharmacy entities), and billing_group_id → member_group (semantic match but could also be billing_account). LOW confidence resolution (1 out of 45): workflow_id → contract.approval_workflow (only one workflow table exists but status_history could reference other workflow types). NULL resolutions (6 out of 45) are system/audit columns or polymorphic FKs with high confidence they should remain unlinked. The main uncertainty areas are: (1) user_id columns mapped to service.agent - while agents are users, there may be other user/employee tables not visible in this model; (2) facility_id and pharmacy_id mappings rely on domain-level resolution where multiple entities could represent these concepts; (3) workflow_id has low confidence as status_history is generic and could reference multiple workflow types. All resolutions follow the mandatory 3-pass evaluation methodology and avoid the documented failure patterns (no PKs sent for resolution, no forced system/audit matches, no self-contradicting reasoning, proper ends-with checking)."
"BATCH_SEMANTIC_FK_RESOLUTION","2","*","*","92","I am highly confident in these resolutions (92%). The majority of matches are HIGH confidence based on clear ends-with PK matching (member_id → member.member_profile, provider_id → provider.provider_profile) or strong semantic equivalences (subscriber_id → member, broker_agent_id → broker).   Key confidence factors: 1. Strong domain knowledge application: Health insurance terminology is well-understood (subscriber=member, plan_benefit_package=benefit_package) 2. Proper handling of system/audit columns: All *_by_user_id, source_system_id, and external system references correctly resolved to null 3. Self-referential FKs correctly identified: previous_assignment_id, reversed_adjustment_id, superseded_plan_id 4. Domain-level resolution applied appropriately: authorization_id → authorization.request (primary entity in authorization domain) 5. No forced matches: External references (CMS, EDI, batch processing) correctly left as null  Areas of slight uncertainty (reducing score from 100% to 92%): 1. MEDIUM confidence on batch_id → claim.claim_batch: Batch processing could be more generic, but claim_batch is the only batch entity available 2. MEDIUM confidence on autopay_enrollment_id → enrollment.enrollment: Autopay might warrant its own entity, but enrollment is semantically reasonable 3. encounter_id left as null: Clinical encounters are core to healthcare but no encounter table exists - this is correct but represents a potential gap in the model 4. payment_plan_id left as null: Payment plans are referenced multiple times but no table exists - should potentially be created but doesn't meet the 'multiple references + core business' threshold strictly  No contradictions between target_table assignments and semantic_reasoning. All resolutions follow the 3-pass evaluation methodology."
"BATCH_SEMANTIC_FK_RESOLUTION","3","*","*","82","I am 82% confident in these resolutions. HIGH confidence resolutions (ends-with matches, self-references, clear semantic matches like state_filing_id → regulatory_filing) are very strong. MEDIUM confidence resolutions (domain-level matches like member_id → member_profile, plan_id → product_plan, provider_id → provider_profile) are well-reasoned based on domain structure, though the PK name mismatch is expected per the rules. The main uncertainties are: (1) Network_id - no standalone network entity exists, which is unusual for such a frequently referenced concept, but I'm confident returning null is correct rather than forcing a match. (2) Tax_id in group_practice - I matched it to member.tax_info with LOW confidence because it's a cross-domain match and provider tax info may be conceptually different from member tax info. (3) User/agent columns - I matched user_id columns to service.agent with MEDIUM confidence as this seems the best semantic fit for system users, though a dedicated user/employee table might be more appropriate. (4) All external system references (EDI, CMS, HIOS, CAQH, clearinghouse, marketplace, source_system) are confidently returned as null per the rules about not forcing matches for external references. No tables_to_create were suggested because the missing concepts (network, service_area, ACO, payer organization) either: (a) are managed through relationship tables rather than core entities, (b) are external references that shouldn't be internalized, or (c) don't meet the threshold of being core operational entities central to Healthcare's primary mission."
"BATCH_SEMANTIC_FK_RESOLUTION","4","*","*","82","I am 82% confident in these resolutions. HIGH CONFIDENCE areas: (1) Member/subscriber references are clearly resolved to member.member_profile - this is a core health insurance concept with strong semantic alignment. (2) Provider references are direct ends-with matches. (3) Self-referential FKs are mechanically correct. (4) System/audit columns (user_id, source_system_id) are correctly identified as external references with no matching tables. (5) Fraud case references to shared.case are semantically sound. MEDIUM CONFIDENCE areas: (1) fraud.rule_violation.batch_id → claim.claim_batch is a reasonable match but could reference other batch types. (2) compliance.compliance_exception.related_incident_id → compliance.breach_incident assumes incidents are breach-related, but could be other incident types. UNCERTAINTY areas: (1) Multiple user_id columns could potentially reference service.agent or other staff tables, but no clear employee/user table exists. (2) Transaction_id references are ambiguous - could reference various transaction types. (3) Some domain-specific entities (training_module, workflow, notification_template) are marked as missing but could potentially map to existing tables with different naming. (4) The distinction between operational staff tables (employee, analyst, investigator) vs external user references required judgment calls. I applied the rule that core operational staff should have a table, while generic user audit columns should remain external. The score reflects high confidence in the semantic matching methodology and member/provider/case resolutions, with moderate uncertainty around missing operational entities and some ambiguous references."
"BATCH_SEMANTIC_FK_RESOLUTION","5","*","*","82","I am 82% confident in these resolutions. HIGH confidence matches (provider_id, program_id, agent_id exact matches, self-references) are solid with clear ends-with PK matching. MEDIUM confidence matches (member_id → member_profile, benefit_plan_id → product_plan, user/reviewer/manager roles → service.agent) are based on domain-level resolution and semantic reasoning appropriate for health insurance context. The main uncertainties are: (1) Multiple user/staff role columns (reviewer_id, case_manager_id, care_manager_id, assessor_id) all mapped to service.agent - while semantically correct, there may be a more specialized staff/user table not visible in the model. (2) Benefit_plan_id and plan_id mapped to product.product_plan despite PK name mismatch - this is domain-level resolution which is valid but introduces some uncertainty. (3) Several system/audit columns and external references correctly identified as null, but there's always risk of missing a subtle internal relationship. (4) Document_reference_id mapped to contract.document with LOW confidence due to weak semantic match. Overall, the resolution follows the prescribed methodology rigorously, with appropriate use of ends-with matching, domain-level resolution, and semantic reasoning while avoiding forced matches for system/audit columns."
"BATCH_SEMANTIC_FK_RESOLUTION","6","*","*","92","I am highly confident in these resolutions (92%). The analysis followed a rigorous 3-pass methodology: (1) ends-with PK matching, (2) domain-level resolution, (3) semantic matching, and (4) system/audit column identification.   Key confidence factors: - HIGH confidence matches (85+ resolutions): Clear ends-with matches (e.g., member_id → member_profile, group_id → member_group, plan_id → product_plan), well-established semantic equivalences (subscriber = member, PCP = provider), and self-referential FKs were straightforward. - MEDIUM confidence matches (1 resolution): employer_id → member_group is a domain-level resolution where employer groups are represented within the member_group table, which is a reasonable but not exact match. - NULL resolutions: Extensive use of null for system/audit columns (source_system_id, legacy_system_id, created_by_user_id), external identifiers (exchange_assigned_policy_id, medicare_id, medicaid_id, EDI trading partner IDs), technical references (session_id, api_request_id, transaction_id), and peripheral systems (device_id, card_id, biometric_id) follows the mandate to avoid forced matches.  Areas of slight uncertainty (8% deduction): - No user/employee table exists, so all user_id references return null. If a user table were added, several resolutions would change. - Some transaction_id and batch_id columns could potentially link to future transaction management tables if they were added to the model. - The employer_id → member_group resolution is semantically reasonable but represents a domain-level match rather than an exact entity match.  The analysis avoided all documented failure patterns: no PKs were treated as FKs, no system/audit columns were forced to inappropriate matches, no cross-domain mismatches were made (e.g., enrollment batch ≠ claim batch, API request ≠ authorization request, enrollment segment ≠ marketing segment), and all resolutions have consistent semantic_reasoning that aligns with the target_table value."
"BATCH_SEMANTIC_FK_RESOLUTION","7","*","*","82","I am 82% confident in these resolutions. HIGH confidence areas: (1) provider_id matches to provider.provider are clear and unambiguous (15+ instances), (2) self-references with exact PK name matches (upline_broker_id, replacement_document_type_id, legacy_fee_schedule_id), (3) system/audit columns correctly identified as null (source_system_id, created_by, etc.), (4) external system references correctly identified (CAQH, CMS, HIOS, Medicaid, marketplace, EDI), (5) semantic match of subscriber_id → member and agent → broker are industry-standard equivalences. MEDIUM confidence areas: (1) domain-level resolutions (member_id, plan_id, product_id) where the FK doesn't end with the exact PK but the domain match is clear - these follow the documented pattern but involve interpretation, (2) authorization_id → authorization.request where authorization could refer to multiple entities in that domain, (3) previous_version_id and original_payment_id self-references where the semantic intent is clear but not explicitly documented. UNCERTAINTY areas: (1) network_id has no clear target - product.plan_network is a mapping table, not a network master, but I didn't suggest creating a network table because it's referenced only 3 times and may be handled differently, (2) reviewer_id, user_id references - these clearly need a user/employee table but it's completely absent from the model, suggesting it may be in a separate identity management system, (3) account_id and group_id ambiguity where multiple interpretations are possible. The two suggested tables (credentialing_application and employer_group) are high-confidence recommendations - both are core business entities with multiple references and central to Healthcare's operations."
"BATCH_SEMANTIC_FK_RESOLUTION","8","*","*","82","I am 82% confident in these resolutions. HIGH CONFIDENCE areas: (1) Domain-level resolutions for member_id → member.member_profile are mechanically sound and well-supported by the domain structure. (2) Ends-with matches like agent_id → service.agent, program_id → shared.program, and self-referential FKs are clear and unambiguous. (3) System/audit column identification (created_by_user_id, source_system_id, etc.) is consistent and follows the rules. (4) External identifier recognition (Medicare IDs, Medicaid IDs, HIOS IDs, CMS material IDs) is appropriate. MEDIUM CONFIDENCE areas: (1) Semantic matches like subscriber_id → member.member_profile and cardholder_id → member.member_profile are reasonable but involve interpretation of business terminology. (2) Plan_id → product.product_plan matches are semantically sound but involve PK name mismatch (plan_id vs product_plan_id). (3) Creative/template → marketing_asset matches involve semantic interpretation of what constitutes a marketing asset. (4) PCMH practice → group_practice is a reasonable semantic match but involves domain knowledge. UNCERTAINTY areas: (1) Some borderline cases like letter_template_id and survey_question_id were resolved as null (not core enough for table creation) but could potentially warrant entities if more context were available. (2) The distinction between identifiers (tax_id, ncpdp_id) and foreign keys required judgment calls. (3) Tables_to_create decisions involved judgment about what constitutes 'core business operations' - I included employer_group, network, ACO, payer, enrollment_application, and PBM as clearly core to health insurance operations, but excluded peripheral systems. Overall, the resolutions follow the methodology rigorously, apply industry knowledge appropriately, and avoid the documented failure patterns (no PKs as FKs, no forced matches, no self-contradictions, proper ends-with checking)."
"BATCH_SEMANTIC_FK_RESOLUTION","9","*","*","78","I am moderately confident (78%) in these resolutions for the following reasons:  STRENGTHS: 1. High confidence matches (85%+): Clear ends-with PK matches (pharmacy_ncpdp_id → location_pharmacy, provider_id → provider, investigation_id → investigation) and self-referential FKs (original_claim_line_id, parent_rule_id, reversal_journal_id) are straightforward and well-supported.  2. Domain-level resolutions (70-80%): Multiple member_id, plan_id references were resolved using domain-level matching to member.member_profile and product.product_plan. These follow the documented pattern where FK columns use domain names as prefixes.  3. System/audit column identification (90%+): Correctly identified and returned null for source_system_id, source_transaction_id, created_by_user_id, approved_by_user_id, etc. - avoiding the past failure of forcing inappropriate matches.  4. External registry codes (90%+): Correctly identified NCPDP, NABP, HIOS, PECOS, EDI payer IDs as external registry codes rather than internal FKs.  WEAKNESSES AND UNCERTAINTIES: 1. Missing employee/user table (major gap): 15+ columns reference employees/users (manager_employee_id, custodian_employee_id, clinical_reviewer_id, uploaded_by_user_id, etc.) but no employee/user/staff table exists. Returned null for all, but this represents a significant gap in the model.  2. Vendor matching ambiguity (60-70% confidence): Matched manufacturer_id, collection_agency_id, and clearinghouse_id to marketing.vendor with MEDIUM/LOW confidence. While semantically reasonable (these are external business entities), the marketing.vendor table may be intended primarily for marketing vendors, not operational vendors.  3. ACO to group_practice (70% confidence): Matched aco_id to provider.group_practice with MEDIUM confidence. While ACOs are provider organizations, they're a specific regulatory construct that may warrant their own table. Only 2 references exist, so didn't suggest table creation.  4. Tax ID references (75% confidence): Matched vendor_tax_id and pharmacy_tax_id to their respective entities (vendor, location_pharmacy) with MEDIUM confidence. These are alternate identifiers rather than true FKs, but the semantic intent is clear.  5. Prescription table gap: pharmacy.refill_request.prescription_id has no target. Prescription is a core pharmacy concept but only referenced once, so didn't meet the threshold for table creation suggestion.  6. Ledger, payer, reporting_entity ambiguities: Several business concepts (ledger_id, payer_id, reporting_entity_id) have no clear matches. These may represent missing master data tables or may be external references.  The 78% score reflects high confidence in the mechanical matches (ends-with, self-references, system columns) but moderate uncertainty in semantic matches involving vendors, organizational entities, and the significant gap of missing employee/user tables. The resolutions follow the documented rules and avoid past failures, but the model itself has structural gaps that limit resolution completeness."
"BATCH_SEMANTIC_FK_RESOLUTION","10","*","*","82","I am 82% confident in these resolutions. HIGH confidence resolutions (approximately 70% of total) include: (1) exact PK name matches (e.g., provider_id → shared.provider.provider_id), (2) clear domain-level resolutions (e.g., member_id → member.member_profile), (3) self-referential FKs (e.g., parent_category_id → service.category), and (4) well-established semantic matches (e.g., medicare_beneficiary_id → member.member_profile, grievance_id → shared.complaint). MEDIUM confidence resolutions (approximately 20%) include: (1) user_id/assigner_id/assignee_id → service.agent (reasonable but no dedicated user table), (2) authorization_id → authorization.request (domain-level match but PK name differs), (3) employer_group_id → member.member_group (semantic fit but could be more specific), and (4) state_medicaid_provider_id → shared.provider (could be external ID). LOW confidence resolutions (approximately 2%) include: knowledge_usage.event_id → service.metric_event (uncertain due to multiple event tables across domains). NULL resolutions (approximately 8%) are highly confident - these are clearly system/audit columns (source_system_id, created_by_user_id, modified_by_user_id, source_record_id), external system references (active_directory_id, cms_transaction_id, medicaid_id), peripheral equipment (workstation_id), technical identifiers (session_id, message_id), or external media storage (call_recording_id, recording_id). The two suggested tables (shared.payment_batch and service.team) are warranted by multiple references and represent core operational concepts. Uncertainty factors: (1) some user/agent mappings rely on semantic interpretation without explicit user tables, (2) team_id resolution to null rather than care.care_team required careful domain context analysis, (3) some external vs internal ID distinctions (e.g., medicaid_id, caqh_provider_id) required industry knowledge, and (4) one LOW confidence match (knowledge_usage.event_id) where multiple event tables exist across domains."
"ATTRIBUTES_SMART_WORKER_PROMPT","428","provider","provider","92","I have generated a comprehensive provider master schema with 103 attributes covering all major categories: identifiers (NPI, TIN, license numbers, DEA), demographics (name, gender, DOB), contact information (addresses, phone, email), taxonomy and specialty, credentialing and licensing, network participation, quality and performance indicators, contract details, panel management, directory display, claims submission, malpractice insurance, sanctions screening, and audit fields. The schema aligns with the operational systems mentioned (Facets, QNXT, HealthEdge, Availity) and reflects industry standards from CMS, NCQA, NPPES, HIPAA, state licensing boards, and other governing bodies. All attributes have genuine business value for provider network management, credentialing, directory maintenance, and claims processing. I followed all naming conventions (no product prefix except for provider_id), applied appropriate PII/PHI classifications (restricted tags for NPI, TIN, names, addresses, phone, email, DOB, license numbers), used proper data types, and included comprehensive value_regex patterns and business glossary terms with full abbreviation expansions. I avoided semantic duplicates and excluded technical/ETL fields. The only minor consideration is that some edge-case attributes (e.g., specific board certification details beyond primary) could potentially be expanded further, but the current coverage represents a production-ready, comprehensive provider master table suitable for a health insurance payer's lakehouse silver layer."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","1","member","*","92","Complete analysis of all 16 products in the member domain. Identified 2 genuinely siloed products (member_note and tax_info) that lack FK to member_profile and added those links. All existing FKs were preserved and not re-included. No bidirectional violations, no self-references, no cross-domain links. The member_note and tax_info products were clearly disconnected from the relational graph and required FKs to member_profile to establish ownership. All other products already have proper FK relationships through the extensive existing FK links. Candidate_evaluation was populated before links array, and only INCLUDE items were transferred. Minor deduction for the fact that member_note and tax_info both have redundant member_id columns that could theoretically be removed, but since member_profile_id is being added as new, the member_id columns may serve as legacy identifiers during migration, so conservative approach was taken to not remove them immediately."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","2","pharmacy","*","88","Complete systematic evaluation of all products in pharmacy domain. All existing cross-domain FKs preserved. Identified 1 genuine new in-domain FK (claim_txn.claim_status_id → claim_status). Made conservative decisions on several borderline cases: (1) NDC attributes treated as natural keys for point-in-time transactional capture rather than FKs to drug table - this is a judgment call as NDC could be modeled either way, but transactional tables typically capture NDC at transaction time for auditability; (2) NPI attributes treated as natural keys rather than FKs to location_pharmacy - again a judgment call, but NPI is the industry standard identifier and is often denormalized for performance; (3) prior_authorization_number treated as string identifier rather than FK to prior_auth_req - this is because the number is a business identifier that may reference external systems. No rule violations: no self-references, no bidirectional links, no cross-domain links, no existing FK re-inclusions. Used candidate_evaluation properly before populating links array. The conservative approach on NDC/NPI is defensible but could be debated by domain experts, hence 88% rather than 95%."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","3","care","*","92","This analysis is comprehensive and follows all critical rules. I systematically evaluated all products in the care domain, used candidate_evaluation to make INCLUDE/EXCLUDE decisions before populating the links array, avoided all bidirectional violations, avoided self-referencing links, and did not re-include existing FKs. All 20 links in the output are genuine INCLUDE decisions with strong business justification. The links normalize reference data (assessment_type, intervention_type, care_event_type, outreach_channel, risk_score_type) and establish critical operational relationships (assessment→intervention, outreach→cohort, intervention→program_goal). No products are siloed - all reference tables have incoming FKs, all transactional tables have outgoing FKs. The potential_many_to_many array is empty because no genuine M:N relationships exist in this domain (all relationships are 1:N with clear parent-child semantics). Column removal is conservative and appropriate - only removing columns that are clearly redundant after FK normalization (e.g., assessment_type STRING replaced by assessment_type_id FK). I score 92% rather than 95%+ because: (1) some links like outreach_contact→program_goal_id are borderline judgment calls where the relationship may not always be present, and (2) I cannot see all attributes for products with '...and N more attributes' so there may be additional normalization opportunities I missed. However, all links included are valid and justified, with no rule violations."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","4","authorization","*","92","Complete analysis of all 23 products in the authorization domain. All existing FKs preserved (no re-inclusion). Identified 47 new FK relationships connecting transactional tables to reference tables for normalization. All reference tables (clinical_guideline, auth_status, denial_reason, approval_reason, request_type, service_type, care_setting, priority_level) now have inbound FKs, eliminating silos. No bidirectional violations, no self-references, no cross-domain links. All FK naming follows target PK naming convention. Columns_to_remove lists are conservative and validated against visible target table attributes. No M:N relationships identified - all relationships in this domain are 1:N (transactional→reference or child→parent). The candidate_evaluation was completed before populating the links array, and the count matches exactly (47 INCLUDE items = 47 links). Minor deduction for not having full visibility into all attributes (some tables show '...and N more attributes'), but all decisions are based on visible attributes and documented accordingly."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","5","enrollment","*","92","Complete analysis of all 19 products in the enrollment domain. All products now have at least one relationship (inbound or outbound), achieving zero siloed tables. Identified 43 new FK relationships that normalize the domain by replacing STRING code/status columns with proper FK references to reference tables. All links follow proper FK naming conventions (ending with target PK name), avoid bidirectional violations, and do not duplicate existing cross-domain FKs. Conservative column removal focused on columns clearly present in target tables (code, name, description, status). No M:N relationships identified as all relationships in this domain follow clear parent-child or reference patterns. The candidate_evaluation was completed before populating the links array, and all 43 links marked INCLUDE were transferred to the output. Minor uncertainty exists around whether some transactional tables (event, change_detail) should retain certain code columns for point-in-time capture, but the normalization approach taken is standard for reference data management."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","6","contract","*","92","Complete analysis of all 30 products in the contract domain. All products now have at least one relationship (inbound or outbound), achieving zero siloed tables. Identified 67 new in-domain FK relationships following proper normalization principles. All links follow the rules: no self-references, no bidirectional violations, no cross-domain links, no re-inclusion of existing FKs. Used candidate_evaluation field properly to evaluate all potential links before populating the links array. Conservative on M:N detection - no genuine M:N relationships identified in this domain (contract_party participation in agreements is handled via FK references to primary/secondary parties rather than a true association table). Minor uncertainty on a few borderline decisions (e.g., whether contract_discount/contract_incentive should reference agreement directly or only via term), but made consistent conservative choices. Column removal recommendations are aggressive but validated against visible attributes in target tables. Score reflects high confidence in structural correctness and completeness of analysis."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","7","eligibility","*","88","Complete analysis of all 10 products in eligibility domain. All products now have relationships (inbound or outbound). Identified 6 new in-domain FK links that normalize duplicated coverage, termination, and event details. No bidirectional violations, no self-references, no cross-domain links, no re-inclusion of existing FKs. Used candidate_evaluation to pre-filter all decisions before populating links array. Minor uncertainty: eligibility_status_code appears to be a reference table but no visible FK columns reference it (products use STRING status fields instead of FK to status codes) - this may indicate denormalization in the source schema or that status code lookups happen at application layer. Also, cob_rule appears to be reference data but no transactional tables visibly reference it via FK - may be applied programmatically. These are borderline architectural decisions about whether to add new FKs to reference tables when current schema uses STRING lookups, which is a valid judgment call in data modeling."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","8","service","*","92","The service domain is exceptionally well-modeled with comprehensive existing FK relationships already in place. I conducted a systematic review of all 18 products and verified that each has at least one relationship (inbound or outbound). The candidate_evaluation was completed before populating the links array, and only one genuinely new FK was identified (interaction.queue_id → queue). I verified no bidirectional violations, no self-references, no cross-domain links, and no re-inclusion of existing FKs. The single link added follows proper FK naming conventions (ends with target PK), includes appropriate column removal (queue_name), and has strong business justification. The domain has zero siloed tables. Minor deduction (8 points) because: (1) interaction already has a queue_name attribute that I'm proposing to replace with queue_id, but there's a possibility the existing design intentionally captures the queue name at interaction time for historical accuracy (point-in-time value), though I believe the FK approach is still superior for referential integrity; (2) I cannot see all attributes of all products (some show '...and X more attributes'), so there's a small possibility of missed relationships in the hidden attributes. However, based on visible attributes and business semantics, the analysis is thorough and correct."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","9","product","*","92","Complete analysis of all 19 products in the product domain. All links in the output array were marked INCLUDE in candidate_evaluation (count matches: 11). No bidirectional violations, no self-references, no cross-domain links, no re-inclusion of existing FKs. All products are now connected (rider was previously siloed, now linked to product_plan). Conservative decisions made on several borderline cases (e.g., not linking enrollment_window to product_plan due to lack of visible FK column, treating cost_sharing as having multiple simultaneous cost_sharing_type references rather than a single FK). The cost_sharing → cost_sharing_type link uses deductible_type as the representative FK, but acknowledged that cost_sharing has multiple type columns representing different mechanisms. Minor uncertainty on whether enrollment_window should have a product_plan_id FK (not visible in attributes, but enrollment windows are typically plan-specific in business operations) - chose conservative approach of not adding it without visible evidence. All structural rules followed, output is clean and production-ready."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","10","quality","*","92","Complete analysis of all 16 products in quality domain. All products now have at least one relationship (inbound or outbound), achieving zero siloed tables. Used candidate_evaluation to systematically evaluate all potential links before populating links array. No self-contradicting entries, no bidirectional violations, no existing FK re-inclusions, no cross-domain links in this step. All 18 new links have clear business justification and proper normalization with columns_to_remove identified. Conservative on M:N detection - found no genuine M:N relationships in this domain (quality measures, scores, and improvement plans follow hierarchical 1:N patterns). Minor uncertainty on whether improvement_action.plan_id should be standardized to improvement_plan_id (both columns exist in the schema), but this is a reasonable judgment call. Score reflects thorough, rule-compliant analysis with proper use of candidate_evaluation framework."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","11","provider","*","88","Complete analysis of all products in the provider domain with systematic evaluation of potential links. All 20 new FK relationships are genuine INCLUDE decisions with clear business justification. No bidirectional violations, no self-references, no cross-domain links, no re-inclusion of existing FKs. Used candidate_evaluation field properly to make all INCLUDE/EXCLUDE decisions before populating links array. Minor uncertainty exists around the provider vs provider_profile relationship - both appear to be master entities with overlapping purposes, and the existing FK structure shows products linking to both. The decision to link provider_profile → provider is based on provider being described as 'Master reference table' with more comprehensive attributes, but this could be a judgment call. All other links are straightforward normalization of reference data (taxonomy, specialty) or establishing clear parent-child relationships (location → provider_profile, credential_summary → provider_profile). No M:N relationships identified - all relationships in this domain are clear 1:N ownership or reference patterns. Deducting 12 points for the provider/provider_profile ambiguity which represents genuine structural uncertainty in the domain model."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","12","claim","*","88","Complete analysis of all 14 products in the claim domain. Successfully identified 12 new in-domain FK relationships, primarily linking transactional tables to reference/lookup tables (claim_diagnosis, claim_procedure, claim_denial_reason) and establishing the critical claim→claim_batch relationship. All existing FK links were preserved without recreation. No bidirectional violations, no self-references (except valid self-references in existing links), no cross-domain links in output. One product (claim_fwa_flag) remains siloed as it is a pure reference table with no visible FK columns in the transactional tables that would reference it - this is acknowledged as a limitation of the visible schema. The claim_batch_id addition to claim is marked as is_new_attribute=true with clear business justification. Code-based references (denial_reason_code, procedure_code, diagnosis_code) correctly identified as FK relationships to lookup tables. Minor uncertainty: claim_line_number fields in several tables were evaluated as integer sequences rather than FKs to claim_line.claim_line_id - this is a judgment call as line_number could theoretically be used for joins, but semantically it represents position within a claim rather than a true FK relationship. Scoring 88% due to the one siloed table and the line_number judgment call, but overall analysis is thorough and structurally sound."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","13","credentialing","*","92","Complete analysis of all 24 products in the credentialing domain. Used candidate_evaluation to systematically evaluate all potential in-domain links before populating the links array. All 23 links in the output are genuine INCLUDE decisions with no SKIP/OMIT entries. No bidirectional violations detected (checked existing FKs before proposing new links). No self-referencing links included. All target products are within the credentialing domain (no cross-domain links). Delta mode respected - did not re-include existing FKs. Identified appropriate columns_to_remove based on visible attributes in target tables, being conservative where target table attributes were not fully visible. All products are now connected with no siloed tables. No M:N relationships identified as this domain is primarily hierarchical (credential as hub with verification events, decisions, reviews as children). Minor uncertainty on a few column removal decisions where target table attributes were partially visible, but overall normalization logic is sound. Count verification: candidate_evaluation stated 23 links, output contains 23 links."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","14","fraud","*","92","Complete analysis of all 16 products in the fraud domain. All products now have at least one relationship (inbound or outbound). The analysis identified 38 new FK relationships that normalize the fraud domain by: (1) linking transactional/operational entities to the investigation master entity, (2) replacing string-based fraud_type and severity_level columns with proper FK relationships to reference tables, and (3) establishing parent-child relationships between recovery records and recovery actions. No bidirectional violations, no self-references, no cross-domain links, and no re-inclusion of existing FKs. The candidate_evaluation was populated before the links array, and all 38 links in the array were marked INCLUDE in the evaluation. Minor uncertainty exists around whether some existing case_id FKs to shared.case should be replaced vs. supplemented with investigation_id FKs - I chose to add investigation_id as a supplemental FK to provide fraud-specific context while preserving existing shared.case links. This is a conservative, valid architectural decision."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","15","risk","*","92","Complete analysis of all 15 products in the risk domain. All products are connected with no silos. Identified 24 new FK relationships that establish proper normalization and referential integrity. Key achievements: (1) Linked all transactional tables to their reference tables (diagnosis_code, hcc_category, model_version), (2) Established traceability chains (diagnosis_record → member_hcc_assignment → member_risk_profile → risk_payment → risk_reconciliation), (3) Connected submission hierarchy (risk_adjustment_submission → raps_submission/edps_submission), (4) Linked exceptions to their source records. All existing FKs preserved. No bidirectional violations, no self-references, no cross-domain links. Used candidate_evaluation to pre-filter all decisions before populating links array. Minor uncertainty on whether diagnosis_code should link to hcc_category (decided yes for authoritative mapping) - this is a reasonable judgment call in a complex risk adjustment domain. Score reflects thorough, rule-compliant analysis with proper normalization decisions."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","16","compliance","*","92","Complete analysis of all 18 products in compliance domain. All products now have at least one relationship (inbound or outbound). Identified 20 new in-domain FK links that were missing. No bidirectional violations introduced (verified each link against existing FKs). No self-referencing links. No cross-domain links in output (all cross-domain FKs preserved in existing links). Used candidate_evaluation to pre-filter all 28 candidates before populating links array - only INCLUDE items transferred. Conservative on column removal (only removed columns where target table clearly contains the data). No M:N relationships identified - compliance domain relationships are primarily hierarchical (policy→version, finding→CAP, incident→notification). Minor uncertainty on whether third_party_risk and vendor_compliance should link to each other (both reference vendor) - chose to exclude to avoid potential cycle. Score reflects thorough, rule-compliant analysis with conservative decisions on ambiguous cases."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","17","government","*","92","Complete systematic evaluation of all product pairs in the government domain. All existing FKs preserved. Identified one genuine missing in-domain FK (provider_program_participation → program_provider_contract) with proper normalization. No bidirectional violations, no self-references, no cross-domain links in output. All products remain connected through existing or new relationships. The domain is heavily interconnected through existing FKs to member_profile and benefit_package, which serve as hub entities. Conservative on M:N detection - no genuine M:N relationships identified within this domain (relationships are primarily transactional child→parent patterns). Minor uncertainty on whether contract_number removal is aggressive enough, but target table program_provider_contract clearly contains contract_number as authoritative source, so normalization is valid. Score reflects high confidence in completeness and correctness of analysis."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","18","sales","*","92","Complete systematic evaluation of all 19 products in sales domain. All products now have at least one relationship (inbound or outbound), achieving zero-silo requirement. Identified 52 new FK relationships following normalization principles. All links follow correct directionality (child→parent), no bidirectional conflicts, no self-references, no cross-domain links. Used candidate_evaluation field properly to evaluate all potential links before populating links array. Column removal recommendations are aggressive but validated against visible attributes. No M:N relationships identified - all relationships in sales domain are hierarchical (opportunity→quote, order→opportunity, payment→policy, etc.). Minor uncertainty on a few borderline cases (e.g., whether proposal should link to opportunity given existing opportunity→proposal link, resolved by excluding to avoid bidirectional), but these are conservative judgment calls, not errors. Output is production-ready."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","19","quality","*","88","Complete systematic evaluation of all 16 products in quality domain. Used candidate_evaluation to assess 27 potential links before populating links array. All 14 links in output were marked INCLUDE in candidate_evaluation - no self-contradicting entries. No bidirectional violations (checked existing FKs and avoided reverse links). No existing FK re-inclusions. No cross-domain links. No self-references. All products now connected (zero siloed tables). Conservative on M:N detection - found no genuine M:N relationships in this domain (quality measures, scores, and improvement plans follow hierarchical 1:N patterns). Minor judgment calls: (1) improvement_action.plan_id exists but not standardized to improvement_plan_id - chose to link it as-is rather than propose column rename; (2) satisfaction_score has both hedis_measure_code and stars_measure_code - added separate FKs for each rather than single measure_id; (3) report_submission and governance_policy may relate to multiple measures but added primary_measure_id FK for primary relationship. These are reasonable architectural decisions where experts could disagree. Columns_to_remove lists are aggressive but validated against visible target table attributes. Score reflects thorough, rule-compliant analysis with proper use of candidate_evaluation framework and no structural violations."
"IN_DOMAIN_LINKING_SMART_PROMPT","20","product","*","92","Complete systematic analysis of all 19 products in the product domain. Successfully identified and resolved the siloed eligibility_criteria product flagged in validation error by linking to plan_type. Also connected rate_schedule_type which was previously siloed. All 21 new FK links follow normalization principles with appropriate columns_to_remove. No bidirectional violations, no self-references, no existing FK re-inclusions. Used candidate_evaluation properly before populating links array. Minor uncertainty on benefit/coverage_limit cost_sharing_type_id links where no direct string column exists but relationship is semantically valid - conservative approach kept columns_to_remove empty in those cases. All products now connected with zero silos. Score reflects high confidence with minor judgment calls on a few links where target table attributes weren't fully visible."
