"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","3","fraud","*","88","All 29 columns classified with decisions. No DROP decisions made (avoiding the MEDIUM confidence DROP trap from past failures). LINK decisions reference either existing tables (member.member_profile) or tables being created in this analysis (fraud.investigator, shared.user). CREATE decisions are for core business entities: user (fundamental), investigator/analyst/reviewer/auditor (specialized fraud roles), transaction (core to fraud detection), subscriber (core health insurance concept). KEEP_AS_IS used appropriately for source_system_id (external system reference) and related_entity_id (polymorphic reference). Minor uncertainty: whether to create separate fraud.investigator/analyst/reviewer/auditor tables vs. linking to a generic workforce.employee - chose CREATE because these are specialized SIU roles with distinct attributes. Also, member_id links to member_profile rather than a dedicated member table, which is the best available match."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","4","eligibility","*","92","All 38 columns were classified with decisions. No DROP decisions were made (avoiding the past failure pattern). LINK decisions point to existing tables (member.member_profile, provider.provider). CREATE decisions are for core health insurance entities (subscriber, network, clearinghouse, payer, plan_sponsor, user, eligibility_rule_set, verification_response). KEEP_AS_IS decisions appropriately handle external system identifiers (EDI, CMS, HIOS, source_system, exchange). Summary counts match actual decisions. The subscriber CREATE appears multiple times but represents the same table to be created. Minor judgment calls on whether clearinghouse/payer should be CREATE vs KEEP_AS_IS, but these are core business partners in health insurance operations."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","5","government","*","87","All 19 columns were classified with decisions. No DROP decisions were made (avoiding the MEDIUM confidence DROP trap). Summary counts match actual decisions. Key judgment calls: (1) segment_id linked to marketing.audience_segment - borderline but reasonable; (2) network_id linked to provider.referral_network - closest available network table; (3) clinical_reviewer_id linked to service.agent - closest person table for internal reviewers. Most government program columns correctly identified as external identifiers (medicaid_id, medicare_beneficiary_id, cms_transaction_id, trading_partner_id, payer_id) which are CMS/EDI references, not internal FKs. No rule violations detected. Minor uncertainty on a few LINK targets where semantic alignment is reasonable but not perfect.'"
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","6","care","*","88","All 29 columns were classified with decisions. No DROP decisions were made (avoiding the MEDIUM confidence DROP trap). LINK decisions all point to existing tables in the model. CREATE decisions (clinical_pathway, payer) are for core business entities that pass the 3-question test. KEEP_AS_IS decisions appropriately handle external system references (source_system, external_, snomed, pbp). One borderline judgment: segment_id linked to marketing.audience_segment with MEDIUM confidence - this is a reasonable interpretation but care-specific segmentation could warrant CREATE. The person/role columns (assessor_id, care_manager_id, etc.) were correctly linked to care.team_member rather than event tables. Summary counts match actual decisions.'"
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","7","finance","*","88","All 35 columns were classified with no missing items. Rules were followed: no DROP decisions were made (avoiding the MEDIUM confidence DROP trap), person/role columns were directed to workforce.employee (CREATE) rather than event tables, self-referencing hierarchies were properly identified with LINK, and external system identifiers were marked KEEP_AS_IS. The audit_trail_id to shared.audit_log links are reasonable but have MEDIUM confidence as audit_trail could be a separate concept. Multiple employee references will CREATE the same table (workforce.employee) which is correct - they all need the same target. Minor judgment calls on source_transaction_id columns (KEEP_AS_IS vs CREATE) but these follow the guidance for 'source' prefixed columns."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","8","compliance","*","88","All 30 columns were classified with decisions. No DROP decisions were made (avoiding the past failure pattern). Self-referencing FKs correctly identified with LINK. Person/role columns correctly identified and routed to CREATE workforce.employee. External system references correctly identified as KEEP_AS_IS. Two MEDIUM confidence decisions exist (related_incident_id linkages to breach_incident) which are judgment calls - breach incidents are the most semantically aligned incident type in the compliance domain, but 'incident' could theoretically mean other things. The test_id CREATE decision is also MEDIUM confidence as the entity name is generic. Summary counts match actual decisions. No rule violations detected."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","9","enrollment","*","88","All 54 columns were classified with decisions. No DROP decisions were made (avoiding the past failure pattern). LINK decisions reference existing tables or tables being created in this analysis. CREATE decisions are for core business entities (enrollment_transaction, enrollment_session, notification_template, enrollment_application, subscriber) that are central to health insurance enrollment operations. KEEP_AS_IS decisions appropriately handle external system references (EDI, exchange, Medicare/Medicaid, source system identifiers). Minor uncertainty exists on segment_id mappings to marketing.audience_segment (could be a different segment concept) and user_id mappings to service.agent (workforce.employee would be ideal but doesn't exist). Summary counts match actual decisions."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","10","credentialing","*","88","All 31 columns are classified with decisions. No DROP decisions were made (avoiding the MEDIUM confidence DROP trap). Summary counts match actual decisions (4 LINK + 18 CREATE + 0 DROP + 9 KEEP_AS_IS = 31). The CREATE decisions for credentialing_application (5 references), delegated_entity (2 references), credentialing_specialist (2 references), network (2 references), notification_template (2 references), and user (3 references) are well-justified by multiple table references. The LINK decisions to service.agent for reviewer_id/verifier_id are judgment calls - no workforce.employee table exists, and service.agent is the closest person table available. The document_reference_id link to contract.document is also a judgment call. Minor deduction for these borderline LINK decisions where CREATE of dedicated tables could also be defensible."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","11","authorization","*","91","All 45 columns were classified with decisions. No DROP decisions were made (avoiding the past failure pattern). All LINK decisions reference existing tables from the provided list. KEEP_AS_IS decisions appropriately identify external system identifiers (source_system_id, correlation_id, message_id, source_transaction_id). Person/role columns (reviewer_id, case_manager_id, approver_id, etc.) were correctly linked to service.agent (a person table) rather than event tables. member_id columns correctly link to member.member_profile. The one borderline judgment call is assigned_to_workgroup_id linking to care.team - this is a reasonable semantic match as workgroups are teams, though a dedicated workgroup table could also be justified. Summary counts match actual decisions (39 LINK, 0 CREATE, 0 DROP, 6 KEEP_AS_IS = 45 total)."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","12","billing","*","88","All 68 columns were classified with decisions. No DROP decisions were made (avoiding the MEDIUM confidence DROP trap). All LINK decisions reference existing tables or tables being created in this analysis. CREATE decisions are for core health insurance business entities (user, subscriber, payment_run, collection_agency, exchange, payer, payment_processor, premium_calculation, third_party_administrator, communication_template). KEEP_AS_IS decisions appropriately handle external system references (EDI, source_system, merchant_account, ACH). Summary counts match actual decisions. Minor uncertainty: billing_run_id linked to payment_run (conceptually similar but not identical) - this is a judgment call. The subscriber CREATE is defensible as subscribers are distinct from member_profiles in health insurance (policyholder vs all covered individuals)."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","13","product","*","92","All 16 columns were analyzed and classified. No columns were dropped (avoiding the MEDIUM confidence DROP trap from past failures). LINK decisions all point to existing tables in the model. CREATE decisions are for 'network' which is a core health insurance concept referenced by 3 tables. KEEP_AS_IS decisions appropriately handle external system identifiers (HIOS, CMS, source_system). Summary counts match actual decisions (7 LINK + 3 CREATE + 6 KEEP_AS_IS = 16). The only minor judgment call was linking plan_id to product_plan rather than care.plan, but product_plan is semantically correct for the product domain context."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","14","quality","*","88","All 6 columns were analyzed and classified. Summary counts match (3 LINK, 0 CREATE, 0 DROP, 3 KEEP_AS_IS = 6 total). All LINK decisions point to existing tables in the model. No DROP decisions were made, avoiding the MEDIUM confidence DROP trap. The entity_id decision is a judgment call - it could arguably be CREATE for a generic entity table, but KEEP_AS_IS is more appropriate for polymorphic references. The member_id link to member_profile is semantically correct as member_profile is the core member entity. Minor uncertainty on whether audit_trail_id should link to audit_log vs audit, but audit_log is more semantically aligned with 'trail' concept."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","15","marketing","*","88","All 40 columns were classified with decisions. No DROP decisions were made (avoiding the past failure pattern). LINK decisions reference existing tables. CREATE decisions are for core marketing entities (creative, email_template, sms_template, survey_question, application). KEEP_AS_IS used appropriately for external system references (user_ids, external_ids, government identifiers like Medicare/Medicaid IDs, CMS material IDs). The segment_owner_id, budget_owner_id, owner_id, and manager_internal_id links to service.agent are reasonable but marked MEDIUM confidence as there's no dedicated workforce.employee table - service.agent is the closest person table for internal staff. Summary counts match actual decisions. Minor uncertainty exists around whether user_id columns should CREATE a user table vs KEEP_AS_IS - chose KEEP_AS_IS as user management is typically external to the data model."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","16","provider","*","88","All 22 columns were classified with no missing items. Summary counts match actual decisions (2 LINK, 10 CREATE, 0 DROP, 10 KEEP_AS_IS). No DROP decisions were made, avoiding the MEDIUM-confidence DROP trap. CREATE decisions were reserved for core business entities (network, ACO, organization, user) that pass the 3-question test. KEEP_AS_IS was appropriately used for external system identifiers (EDI codes, tax IDs, Medicaid/CAQH numbers). Two judgment calls: (1) contract_affiliation_id linked to network_affiliation with MEDIUM confidence - reasonable but could be debated; (2) subscriber_id kept as external reference rather than creating a subscriber table - defensible since member_profile exists. No semantic mismatches or rule violations detected."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","17","pharmacy","*","92","All 40 columns were analyzed and classified. No DROP decisions were made (avoiding the past failure pattern). LINK decisions point to existing tables (member.member_profile, pharmacy.location_pharmacy, shared.audit_log). CREATE decisions are for core business entities (user, pbm, manufacturer, prescription, letter_template) that are central to health insurance pharmacy operations. KEEP_AS_IS decisions correctly identify external identifiers (NCPDP, NABP, tax IDs, source_system_id). The CREATE decisions for user, pbm, manufacturer, and prescription are well-justified as core entities referenced by multiple tables. Minor judgment calls: linking cardholder_id and subscriber_id to member_profile (reasonable as they represent member roles), and audit_trail_id to audit_log (semantic alignment is reasonable). Summary counts match actual decisions."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","18","risk","*","88","All 27 columns are classified with decisions. No DROP decisions were made (avoiding the MEDIUM confidence DROP trap). LINK decisions point to existing tables (adjustment_submission self-reference, reconciliation self-reference, member_profile). CREATE decisions are for core business entities: encounter (fundamental healthcare concept) and user (core for audit trails and workflow). KEEP_AS_IS used appropriately for external system references (CMS, submission files, source systems). The subscriber_id to member_profile link is a reasonable semantic match. One minor uncertainty: source_record_id marked MEDIUM confidence as it could be polymorphic, but KEEP_AS_IS is the safe choice. All summary counts match actual decisions. The 17 CREATE decisions all point to just 2 distinct tables (encounter and user), which is appropriate consolidation."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","19","member","*","88","All 63 columns were classified with decisions. No DROP decisions were made (avoiding the MEDIUM confidence DROP trap). LINK decisions reference existing tables from the model. CREATE decisions are for core business entities (subscriber, employer, user, network, ACO) that are central to health insurance operations. KEEP_AS_IS decisions appropriately handle external system identifiers. One borderline judgment: case_manager_id linked to care.team_member (MEDIUM confidence) - case managers could warrant their own table, but team_member is semantically appropriate. Summary counts match actual decisions. Minor deduction for the case_manager_id judgment call and potential debate on whether some CREATE decisions (like employer) could be KEEP_AS_IS if UHC only references employer IDs from external HR systems."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","20","sales","*","88","All 36 columns were classified with decisions. No DROP decisions were made (avoiding the past failure pattern). LINK decisions point to existing tables. CREATE decisions are for core business entities (sales representatives, underwriters, networks, users, subscribers - all central to health insurance operations). KEEP_AS_IS used appropriately for external system references (source_system, marketplace, medicaid, tax IDs, EDI transactions). One borderline call: segment_id linked to marketing.audience_segment with MEDIUM confidence - could arguably be a different type of segment, but semantic alignment is reasonable. The member_id links to member_profile rather than a dedicated member table, which is the best available match. Summary counts verified: 7 LINK + 17 CREATE + 0 DROP + 12 KEEP_AS_IS = 36 total."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","21","service","*","88","All 54 columns were classified with decisions. No DROP decisions were made (avoiding the past failure pattern). All LINK decisions reference existing tables or tables being created in this analysis. CREATE decisions are for core business entities (employee, department, contact_center, grievance, etc.) that pass the TIER 2 business relevance test. KEEP_AS_IS decisions appropriately handle external system references (source_system_id, call_recording_id, active_directory_id, etc.). The workforce.employee table is referenced multiple times for CREATE - this is intentional as it's a single table that multiple columns should link to. Minor uncertainty exists around whether member_id should link to member_profile vs a dedicated member table, but member_profile appears to be the member entity in this model. Summary counts match actual decisions."
"FIND_MISSING_FK_LINKS","22","shared","*","88","All 52 columns were classified with decisions. No DROP decisions were made (avoiding the MEDIUM confidence DROP trap). LINK decisions reference existing tables from the model. CREATE decisions are for core business entities (user, workflow, facility, pharmacy, payer, payee, segment, survey_question) that are central to health insurance operations. KEEP_AS_IS decisions appropriately handle external system references (source_system_id, cms_formulary_id, medicaid_id, etc.) and technical identifiers (device_id, correlation_id, transaction_id). Minor uncertainty: (1) assigned_care_manager_id linked to care.team_member rather than creating a dedicated care_manager table - reasonable since care managers are team members; (2) Multiple user_id columns all point to CREATE shared.user - this is correct as they all reference the same needed table. Summary counts match actual decisions."
